column2: JAKUBANY FILM 1, 2 & 3 MARRIAGES - 1772-1918 Sorted by Bride (similar surname, first name and date)
Notes: -- From 1832-1877, generally after the bride's name, an * followed by a number is a note number: see notes at the end of the marriages
-- A notation (d) after a parents name indicates that parent was deceased at the time of the marriage of the applicable child
-- The abbreviation wid after the groom/bride's name indicates widow.
-- Different version dates usually means that typos/errors were fixed, skipped records were added, or something was changed herein.
-- NEW SORT - Bride Surnames that begin with Sz in the records will be shown under S and the letter following 'z' in the alphabetical listing.

column3: Likewise, bride surnames that begin with Zs in the records will be found under Z and the letter following 's'.

column2: -- If at first you don't see the bride under the first name you thought it should be under, also look for the hungarian equivalent.  For example,
Anastasia = Nastasia or Nestze; Catharina = Katalin; Helena = Elena, Ilyka; Irene = Orina; Julianna = Ulianna; Susanna = Zuzanna.
-- Surnames will be darkened (bold) at the beginning of any name group where there are 2 or more similar surnames.
-- Latest revision includes "wid" notations in the russian marriage records 1851-1857 which had been left off due to language unfamiliarity.
